In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. Lifecycle events moved to the **`Window`** class. Override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class and hook into Window events:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window)        |
|---------------|---------------------------|
| `OnStart`     | `Created`                 |
| `OnSleep`     | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` |
| `OnResume`    | `Resumed` / `Activated`   |

**Option 1 — Window events:**
```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**
```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }
}
```

**Key difference:** MAUI supports multiple windows, so lifecycle is per-window rather than per-app.
